		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sat, Apr 16th 12:46 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1113591484615675984&num=5&post=1&replyto=1113670013146067223"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1113670013146067223></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=445022"><span id=Scholar>valys</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br />49 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.39]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=valys&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Challenge: yes, definitely. While there's more walk-throughs than their used to be, the game doesn't have nearly the level of hand holding that WoW and EQ2 do. Further, what tutorial and gameplay assistance you get is all aimed at interface related issues; how to move around, how to talk to people, that kind of thing. What it doesn't tell you is where to go, what to kill, what drops what, and so forth. You have to figure that all out for yourself (some of it is obvious - like killing a decaying skeleton to get a Bone Chip - and other stuff is much harder to figure out without asking someone). For the most part, though, you're given a crappy sword or a couple of spells and left to figure things out on your own. ;)<br><br>The challenge continues throughout the game, as you get new equipment, new abilities, new spells, and are forced to move to new areas to gain experience. It gives you alot to figure out, including the lesson that sometimes new is not better (for example a 10 mana/30 damage level 5 spell is more mana efficient than a 75 mana/150 damage level 9 spell). After 6 years, there is SO much in this game that honestly, no one (not even the mighty Czae) knows everything. Most of us have our particular specialties of knowledge, and pooling them together in a group or a guild really gives you alot of information to be successful with.<br><br>The main reason that alot of the people here still play EQ1 is the challenge... the graphics are outdated, it has its problems, yes... but, it's constantly challenging and for many people, challenge = fun, easy = boring.<br><br>Grind; yes. Well, most likely. There will be times when you grind xp. You don't have to, of course, but it's often the most efficient way to level. You could go to 18 different zones in an hour killing 18 different things, but as a general rule you'll get better xp sitting in one spot for that hour killing things over and over.<br><br>Not that xp is everything, some players are very happy levelling at a slow pace while taking time to enjoy the world around them. Others just want to get to 70 as fast as possible. It depends on the person and their playstyle, but most likely there will be points where you will grind to gain xp. How often you do so is entirely up to you. ;)<br><br>Quests and fun: yes to both! Although quests are by no means a primary way to gain gear or xp, they can be a fun diversion and some of them are quite good. You can check out some quests here on Allakhazams... just use the side bar to select Quests -&gt; By Zone -&gt; whatever zone you're spending time in.<br><br>And fun, is, of course, happening all the time. This is a game, if it weren't fun, people wouldn't still be playing after 6 years. ;)<br><br>Welcome to EQ!</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />-<a href="HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=1164496" target="akztarg">Uthil</a>, 52 Halasian Puppymaster &lt;Lucky Insane&gt; Morden Rasp<br>-Valys, 53 Furryfoot Rogue, Bristlebane (retired 10/01)<br></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from The cultural forge in Halas</td></tr></table>
